# Repo Operating Model

- Start any session by reading `AGENTS.md` — it has the repo map, source-of-truth hierarchy, cold-start protocol, routing rules, and current project state.
- For compatibility-only machine context, `agent-manifest.json` and `llms.txt` exist as thin pointers back to `AGENTS.md` and `docs/catalog.json`.
- `docs/catalog.json` is the machine-readable index of the docs tree and routing-critical surfaces.
- Treat this repo as Cursor-first. Shared behavior lives in `AGENTS.md`, `.cursor/rules/`, `docs/ops/agent-operations.md`, and `docs/ops/agent-documentation-contract.md`.
- `CLAUDE.md` is a compatibility surface only. Do not create a second source of truth there.
- Default to docs-first work. Product changes must stay aligned with `docs/vision.md`, `docs/prd-foundation.md`, `docs/roadmap.md`, and `docs/decisions.md`.
- All durable docs under `docs/` use YAML frontmatter. Parse `authority` and `depends_on` before editing to avoid conflicts with upstream docs.
- Keep autonomous work bounded: one task, explicit verification commands, explicit escalation triggers, and a terminal state of `done`, `blocked`, `failed`, or `budget_exhausted`.
- Use Cursor as the human-facing orchestrator. Use Claude Code only as an optional compatibility surface, not the owner of repo policy.
- Repo automation expects `WSL` or Linux with `bash` and `python3`; editing from Windows Cursor is fine, but the repo scripts are not PowerShell-first.
